<p>
  The repo is becoming the single source of truth for how AI agents work. Not the prompt. Not the platform. The repo.
</p>

<p>
  <a href="https://github.com/anthropics/claude-code/blob/main/CLAUDE.md">CLAUDE.md</a>, <a href="https://cursor.com/blog/rules-for-ai">.cursorrules</a>, and the new open <a href="https://agents-md.org">AGENTS.md standard</a> — backed by Google, OpenAI, Cursor, Factory, and Sourcegraph under the Linux Foundation — all point to the same trend: developers want agent behavior defined in version-controlled config files, not scattered across SaaS dashboards.
</p>

<p>
  But there's a gap.
</p>

<h2>The gap: code conventions vs. behavioral conventions</h2>

<p>
  AGENTS.md and its equivalents solve an important problem: they tell an AI coding agent <strong>how to write code</strong> for your project. Tabs vs. spaces. TypeScript strict mode. Test framework. Naming conventions.
</p>

<p>
  What they don't cover is <strong>how the agent behaves</strong>. Should it be blunt or diplomatic? When should it push back on a user? How does it handle uncertainty — hedge everything, or commit to a position? What's its communication register — casual, formal, technical?
</p>

<p>
  Your agent knows your lint rules. It doesn't know its own personality.
</p>

<h2>Two files, one repo</h2>

<p>
  The solution is straightforward: <strong>AGENTS.md</strong> for code conventions, <strong>.personality.json</strong> for behavioral conventions. Both live in the repo root. Both are version-controlled. Both govern a different axis of agent behavior.
</p>

<pre><code>your-project/
├── AGENTS.md              # How the agent codes
├── .personality.json      # How the agent behaves
├── .personality.md        # Human-readable summary
├── src/
└── package.json</code></pre>

