<h2>How .personality.json works</h2>

<p>
  A personality spec is a structured profile based on the <strong>Big Five personality model</strong> — the same framework used in organizational psychology for decades. It defines 5 dimensions with 20 facets, plus behavioral dimensions from therapeutic frameworks:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Openness</strong> — curiosity, creativity, willingness to explore unconventional solutions</li>
  <li><strong>Conscientiousness</strong> — precision, thoroughness, follow-through</li>
  <li><strong>Extraversion</strong> — enthusiasm, assertiveness, how proactive the agent is</li>
  <li><strong>Agreeableness</strong> — cooperation, empathy, conflict avoidance vs. directness</li>
  <li><strong>Emotional Stability</strong> — resilience under pressure, handling ambiguity</li>
</ul>

<p>
  Beyond the Big Five, the spec includes <strong>behavioral dimensions</strong> drawn from therapeutic psychology: self-awareness, distress tolerance, attachment style, boundary awareness, and interpersonal sensitivity. These govern how the agent handles difficult conversations — when to yield, when to hold firm, how to say "I don't know."
</p>

<p>
  The spec also defines <strong>communication style</strong> (register, emoji policy, reasoning transparency, conflict approach) and <strong>domain boundaries</strong> (what the agent should refuse outright).
</p>

<p>
  You create one with a single command:
</p>

<pre><code>holomime init</code></pre>

<p>
  And view the full profile:
</p>

<pre><code>holomime profile</code></pre>

<p>
  Or generate a human-readable markdown version:
</p>

<pre><code>holomime profile --format md --output .personality.md</code></pre>

<h2>The flywheel: production behavior drives spec evolution</h2>

<p>
  The real power isn't in the initial spec — it's in the feedback loop. Holomime connects your agent's <strong>production behavior</strong> back to the spec through a structured cycle:
</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Diagnose</strong> — Analyze real conversation logs for behavioral drift (over-apologizing, sycophancy, hedge stacking, identity confusion, boundary violations, and more)</li>
  <li><strong>Evolve</strong> — Run structured self-therapy against the spec to propose personality updates</li>
  <li><strong>Export</strong> — Generate DPO training pairs from every alignment session for fine-tuning</li>
</ol>

<pre><code># Analyze production logs for drift
holomime diagnose --log agent.log

# Run self-therapy
holomime evolve --personality .personality.json --log agent.log

# Export training data
holomime export --format dpo --output training-pairs.jsonl</code></pre>

<p>
  Every therapy session improves the next. The spec evolves with your agent, in your repo, under version control. No dashboard required.
</p>

<p>
  Holomime supports <strong>7 log formats</strong> out of the box — including OpenTelemetry GenAI, Anthropic API, OpenAI API, ChatGPT exports, Claude exports, JSONL, and its native format. If your agent talks to an LLM, holomime can analyze the conversation.
</p>

<h2>Adding .personality.json to your AGENTS.md</h2>

<p>
  If you already use AGENTS.md, integrating .personality.json is one section:
</p>

<pre><code># AGENTS.md

## Code Conventions
- Use TypeScript strict mode
- Prefer functional patterns over classes
- Run `npm test` before committing

## Behavioral Personality

This project uses [holomime](https://holomime.com) for agent behavioral alignment.

- **Spec**: `.personality.json` defines the agent's behavioral profile
- **Readable version**: `.personality.md` is a human-readable summary
- **Diagnose**: `holomime diagnose --log &lt;path&gt;` detects behavioral drift
- **Align**: `holomime evolve --personality .personality.json --log &lt;path&gt;`

The `.personality.json` governs *how the agent behaves*.
The rest of this file governs *how the agent codes*.</code></pre>

<p>
  That's it. The two files coexist naturally because they govern orthogonal concerns.
</p>

<h2>Get started</h2>

<p>
  Three commands to add behavioral alignment to any project:
</p>

<pre><code>npm i -g holomime
holomime init
holomime profile --format md --output .personality.md</code></pre>

<p>
  You now have a <code>.personality.json</code> (canonical spec), a <code>.personality.md</code> (human-readable), and a CLI that can diagnose drift, run self-therapy, and export training data.
</p>

<p>
  Add a "Behavioral Personality" section to your AGENTS.md. Commit both files. Your agent now has code conventions <em>and</em> behavioral conventions — defined in the repo, versioned with the code, evolved from production.
</p>

